    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Devices of various types designed to decrease the amount of time it takes photographic film to dry after development. These often take the form of a cabinet with provision for forced filtered and heated air to circulate.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000077457/Popular Science [journal] (1872-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000083365/Anchell, The Darkroom Cookbook (2012)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Apparaten van uiteenlopende soort die ontworpen zijn om de droogtijd voor fotografische film na ontwikkeling te verminderen. Ze hebben vaak de vorm van een kast met een voorziening om er gefilterde en verwarmde perslucht door te laten circuleren.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
